I\'92ve used FOI in couple of different ways to help cover COINS, the UK Government\'92s biggest database of spending, budget and financial information. At the beginning of 2010, there was talk from George Osborne that if he became chancellor, he would release the COINS database to facilitate greater transparency in the Treasury. At this time it seemed a good idea to investigate the data in and structure of COINS so I sent a few FOI requests, one for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bit.ly/wdtk-coins-1"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 schema of the database}}, one for the guidance Treasury workers receive when {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bit.ly/wdtk-coins-2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 they work with COINS}}, and one for the Treasury {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bit.ly/wdtk-coins-3"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 contract with the database provider}}. All of which resulted in publication of useful data. I also requested all the spending codes in the database, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://bit.ly/wdtk-coins-4"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 which was also published}}. All of this helped to understand COINS when George Osborne became chancellor in May 2010 and published COINS in June 2010. The COINS data was used in a number of websites encouraging the public to investigate the data\'97including {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://openspending.org/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 OpenSpending.org}} and the Guardian\'92s{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://coins.guardian.co.uk/coins-explorer/search"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Coins Data Explorer}}.\

